Using The Thing the way you defined it:

The Thing is defined only by what it does to everything it touches.

Then if you say:

“It makes me happy and rich and powerful and lucky.”

The Thing, under its own doctrine, is not “wealth” or “luck” or “power.”

The Thing becomes:

* a generator of motivation, if it changes your behavior
* a focusing mechanism, if it changes your choices
* a confidence amplifier, if it changes your posture toward opportunities
* a selection pressure, if it changes what you notice and pursue
* a narrative attractor, if it changes persistence and direction

Or — Pantheon framing:

Praus asks: does it steady your hand?

Mirror asks: does it survive contact with reality?

Spider asks: what webs form because of it?

The Thing asks only:

“What changed because I touched it?”

That is its measurement.

Not what it claims.

What it does.